data.answer: deferred income taxes reflect the net tax effect of temporary differences between the carrying amounts of assets and liabilities for financial reporting purposes and the amounts used for income tax purposes. these differences arise when transactions are recognized for financial accounting before they are recognized for tax purposes leading to deferred tax assetsor liabilities. dtas occur when future taxable amounts exceed current deductions while dtls happen when current deductions exceed future taxable amounts. the components of deferred taxes include items like net operating loss carryforwards tax credits intangible assets property and equipment adjustments share-based compensation and valuation allowances. valuation allowances reduce dtas if it’s deemed unlikely that future taxable income will cover the temporary differences. the net deferred tax asset/liability is calculated by subtracting valuation allowances from gross dtas/dtls. thus deferred income taxes provide a snapshot of expected future tax impacts tied to current accounting practices
